<Base title="How to Review a Freelance Contract in 5 Minutes (Without a Lawyer)" description="A practical guide to reviewing freelance contracts quickly. Learn which clauses to check first, what red flags look like, and how to protect yourself.">
  <article class="blog-post">
    <div class="container">
      <header class="post-header">
        <time datetime="2026-03-23">March 23, 2026</time>
        <h1>How to Review a Freelance Contract in 5 Minutes (Without a Lawyer)</h1>
        <p class="post-lead">You don't need a law degree to protect yourself. Here's a practical, step-by-step process for reviewing any freelance contract quickly and confidently.</p>
      </header>

      <div class="post-body">
        <p>
          A client just sent you a contract. They want it signed by end of day. You're excited about the project, but the PDF is 8 pages of dense legal text and you don't have a lawyer on retainer.
        </p>
        <p>
          Sound familiar? Here's exactly how I review contracts now -- a process that takes about 5 minutes and catches the things that actually matter.
        </p>

        <h2>Step 1: Check the Money (1 minute)</h2>
        <p>Go straight to the payment section. You're looking for:</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Total amount</strong> -- does it match what you discussed?</li>
          <li><strong>Payment schedule</strong> -- when do you get paid? Milestones, monthly, or upon completion?</li>
          <li><strong>Net terms</strong> -- Net-30 is normal. Net-60 is annoying. Net-90 is a red flag.</li>
          <li><strong>Deposit</strong> -- is there one? There should be.</li>
          <li><strong>Late payment</strong> -- any penalties for the client paying late? If not, you have no leverage.</li>
        </ul>
        <p>If the payment terms are vague or unfavorable, flag them before you look at anything else. Money is the reason you're doing this.</p>

        <h2>Step 2: Find the Scope (1 minute)</h2>
        <p>Look for the section that defines what you're actually building or delivering. Check for:</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Specific deliverables</strong> -- are they listed clearly?</li>
          <li><strong>Revision limits</strong> -- how many rounds of revisions are included?</li>
          <li><strong>Change process</strong> -- what happens when the client wants something outside the original scope?</li>
        </ul>
        <p>Vague scope is the #1 source of freelancer pain. If the contract says "deliver a website" without specifying what that means, you need more detail in writing before you sign.</p>

        <h2>Step 3: Scan for IP Clauses (1 minute)</h2>
        <p>Search the document for "intellectual property," "IP," "work product," or "ownership." You're checking:</p>
        <ul>
          <li>Does the client get ownership of the deliverables? (Usually fine.)</li>
          <li>Does the client get ownership of your pre-existing tools, templates, or code? (Not fine.)</li>
          <li>Are you assigning rights to "all work" or just "project deliverables"? The wording matters a lot.</li>
        </ul>
        <p>The ideal clause: the client owns the final deliverables, but you retain a license to your pre-existing IP and can reuse general skills and knowledge.</p>

        <h2>Step 4: Look for Restrictions (1 minute)</h2>
        <p>Search for "non-compete," "non-solicitation," "exclusive," and "confidential." Ask yourself:</p>
        <ul>
          <li>Am I restricted from working with their competitors? For how long?</li>
          <li>Am I restricted from contacting anyone at the client company after the project?</li>
          <li>Is the confidentiality clause so broad that I can't even put this project in my portfolio?</li>
        </ul>
        <p>Non-competes in freelance contracts are more common than you'd think, and they can seriously limit your ability to earn.</p>

        <h2>Step 5: Check the Exit (1 minute)</h2>
        <p>Every contract should answer: what happens if this goes sideways? Look for:</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Termination rights</strong> -- can both parties terminate, or just the client?</li>
          <li><strong>Notice period</strong> -- how much advance notice is required?</li>
          <li><strong>Kill fee</strong> -- if the client cancels mid-project, do you get paid for work completed?</li>
          <li><strong>Liability cap</strong> -- what's the maximum you could owe if something goes wrong?</li>
        </ul>

        <h2>The Fast Track: Use an AI Review Tool</h2>
        <p>
          The 5-step process above works, but I'll be real: it still requires you to read legal language and interpret what it means. Sometimes clauses are deliberately confusing.
        </p>
        <p>
          That's why I built <a href="/fixitdev-site/tools/contractscan">ContractScan</a>. It does this same analysis automatically. Upload your contract PDF, and in about 30 seconds you get:
        </p>
        <ul>
          <li>A risk score from 1-100</li>
          <li>Every red flag highlighted with a plain-English explanation</li>
          <li>Suggested alternative language you can send back to your client</li>
        </ul>
        <p>
          I still recommend understanding what you're signing (that's why I wrote this article). But having an AI do the first pass means you're less likely to miss something buried in page 6 of a 12-page document.
        </p>

        <h2>Quick Reference Checklist</h2>
        <p>Bookmark this for your next contract review:</p>
        <ul>
          <li>Payment amount, schedule, and terms clearly defined?</li>
          <li>Scope and deliverables specific enough?</li>
          <li>IP assignment limited to project deliverables only?</li>
          <li>No unreasonable non-compete or exclusivity?</li>
          <li>Both parties can terminate with fair terms?</li>
          <li>Liability is capped?</li>
          <li>Late payment penalties included?</li>
        </ul>
        <p>If you can check all of those boxes, you're in good shape.</p>

        <div class="post-cta">
          <p><strong>Want the AI version?</strong> <a href="/fixitdev-site/tools/contractscan">Scan your contract for free with ContractScan</a></p>
        </div>
      </div>
